
[1]regiment

   REG'IMENT, n. [L. regimen.]

   1. In military affairs, a body of men, either horse, foot or artillery,
   commanded by a colonel or lieutenant colonel and major, and consisting
   of a number of companies, usually from eight to ten.

   2. Government; mode of ruling; rule; authority; as used by Hooker, Hale
   and others. [Wholly obsolete.]

    REG'IMENT, v.t. To form into a regiment or into regiments with proper
                   officers. [A military use of the word.]
